---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="The Problem" description="Why distributed consensus is hard: failures, partitions, and the impossibility results behind it.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 pt-16 pb-8">
    <p class="text-sky-400 text-sm font-mono mb-3">Chapter 1</p>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-4">The Problem</h1>
    <p class="text-slate-400 text-lg">
      Before understanding Raft, you need to feel the pain it solves.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The setup -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">A simple distributed key-value store</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Imagine you're building a distributed key-value store. You run 3 servers so that if one
      crashes, the system keeps working. Every write goes to all 3 servers, every read can hit any of them.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 p-6 font-mono text-sm mb-6">
      <div class="text-slate-500 mb-3"># client writes</div>
      <div class="text-green-400">SET x = 1   →   [S1, S2, S3]</div>
      <div class="text-green-400">SET x = 2   →   [S1, S2, S3]</div>
      <div class="text-slate-400 mt-3 mb-1"># client reads from any server</div>
      <div class="text-sky-400">GET x from S2  →  2 ✓</div>
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      This looks fine — until things go wrong.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Failure scenarios -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">What can go wrong</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-red-900/40 p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">1. Node crash</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          S2 crashes mid-write. S1 and S3 wrote <code class="text-sky-300">x=2</code>, but S2 still has <code class="text-sky-300">x=1</code>.
          When S2 comes back, it serves stale data. A client reading from S2 gets the wrong answer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-orange-900/40 p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-orange-400 mb-2">2. Network partition</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          A network switch fails and splits your cluster: {"{S1}"} on one side, {"{S2, S3}"} on the other.
          Both sides are alive and healthy. Both sides can receive writes. Now you have two "leaders"
          writing independently — this is called <strong class="text-slate-200">split-brain</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-yellow-900/40 p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-yellow-400 mb-2">3. Slow messages</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          A message takes 10 seconds to arrive (the network is congested, not broken).
          Is S2 dead, or just slow? You can't tell from the outside. If you assume dead and elect a
          new leader, you might end up with two active leaders simultaneously.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The core challenge -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">The core challenge: agreement under uncertainty</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
      The fundamental problem is this: <strong class="text-slate-200">you need multiple nodes to agree on a sequence of values,
      even when nodes fail and messages are delayed or lost.</strong>
      This is called <em>consensus</em>.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-8">
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-3">Safety (correctness)</h4>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">Two nodes must never decide on <em>different</em> values for the same slot. No divergence, ever.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-3">Liveness (progress)</h4>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">If enough nodes are alive and can communicate, the system must eventually make progress and not stall forever.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-700/40 rounded-xl p-5">
      <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-400 mb-2">FLP Impossibility (1985)</h4>
      <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Fischer, Lynch, and Paterson proved that in a fully asynchronous system (where you cannot distinguish
        a crashed node from a slow one), it is <strong class="text-slate-200">impossible</strong> to guarantee
        both safety and liveness simultaneously.
        <br/><br/>
        In practice, systems break this by using <strong class="text-slate-200">timeouts</strong> — they
        <em>assume</em> a node is dead if it doesn't respond in time. This makes the network
        "partially synchronous" and gets around the impossibility.
        Raft is built on this assumption.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CAP theorem -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">CAP Theorem</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-400 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
      During a network partition, you must choose between:
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 p-5 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl mb-2">✅</div>
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-1">Consistency</h4>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">Every read gets the most recent write or an error.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 p-5 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl mb-2">📡</div>
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-1">Availability</h4>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">Every request gets a (non-error) response, even if it might be stale.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-slate-700 p-5 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl mb-2">🔀</div>
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-1">Partition Tolerance</h4>
        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">The system continues to operate even if messages are lost or delayed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-xl border border-sky-800/50 p-5">
      <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-sky-400">Raft chooses CP</strong> — it sacrifices availability to guarantee consistency.
        If the cluster loses quorum (more than half the nodes are unreachable), it stops accepting writes
        rather than risk serving inconsistent data. This is the right trade-off for databases, config stores, and coordination services.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Next -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
      <span class="text-slate-600">←</span>
      <a href={`${base}/raft`} class="px-6 py-3 bg-sky-600 hover:bg-sky-500 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg transition">
        Next: How Raft solves this →
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
